<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<meta charset="utf-8">
<title>Cooper: Access Denied</title>
<style>
* { font-family: monospace; }
body { background: #1a1a1a; color: #d4c5a9; margin: 0; padding: 40px; }
h1 { color: #c87533; font-size: 18px; border-bottom: 1px solid #4a3f2f; padding-bottom: 12px; }
.domain { color: #e8a849; font-weight: bold; }
.section { color: #8b9e7e; margin-top: 20px; font-weight: bold; }
.hint { color: #9a9a9a; margin-left: 16px; line-height: 1.8; }
.action { color: #c87533; margin-left: 16px; line-height: 1.8; }
pre { background: #111; padding: 16px; border-left: 3px solid #c87533; color: #d4c5a9; overflow-x: auto; }
</style>
</head>
<body>

<h1>ACCESS DENIED — Network proxy blocked this request</h1>

<p>Domain: <span class="domain">%H</span></p>
<p>Reason: This domain is not on the proxy whitelist.</p>

<p class="section">Context:</p>
<p class="hint">
You are running inside a network-isolated container managed by Cooper.<br>
All outbound traffic goes through a filtering proxy that only allows whitelisted domains.<br>
This block is intentional — it prevents unauthorized data exfiltration and supply-chain attacks.
</p>

<p class="section">Before requesting access, try these first:</p>
<p class="hint">
1. Complete the task using only local files, cached data, and already-available resources.<br>
2. Check if an alternative whitelisted domain provides what you need.<br>
3. Do not install packages at runtime — dependencies are installed at build time on the host.
</p>

<p class="section">If you truly need access to this domain:</p>
<p class="action">
Tell your user:<br>
</p>
<pre>I need access to %H but it's blocked by the Cooper network proxy.
Please approve it in the Cooper monitor (cooper up → Monitor tab),
or add it permanently via cooper configure → Proxy Whitelist.</pre>

<p class="hint">
Your user can approve the request in real-time from the Monitor tab,<br>
or add the domain permanently via <b>cooper configure</b>.
</p>

</body>
</html>
